Gene and bacteria correlation

Gene and bacteria correlation

Loading package

library(tidyr)

Gene dataset

Importation of gene dataset

We import the raw data frame of genes

gene_df = read.csv(file="../raw_data/Quantifications_and_functional_annotations.tsv",
                   sep="\t",
                   stringsAsFactors = TRUE,
                   nrow = 2000,
                   na.strings = c("NA", "-"))

Manipulations on the gene data set

If we want to use the KEGG_ko instead of the preferred names, set the following to True or T.

Use_kegg = F

After loading the gene dataset, we remove all columns except those containing the number of reads and the columns called “Prefered name” (or KEGG_ko in case Use_kegg = T ). The column contain names for genes.

if (Use_kegg) {
  Column_of_interest = 47
} else {
  Column_of_interest = 44
}

dim_raw = dim(gene_df)[1]
gene_df = gene_df[,c(2:35,Column_of_interest)]

Then we compute the relative abundances.

## Computing relative abundance
for (i in 1:34){
  sum_col = sum(gene_df[,i])
  if (sum_col != 0){
    gene_df[,i] = gene_df[,i]/sum_col
  }
}

If the Prefered_name is use, there is no problem : each row gets one and only one name. BUT if we use the KEGG_Ko , sometimes for the same row, several KO are given. So we need to duplicate the rows where there are different KO.

if (Use_kegg) {
  gene_df = separate_rows(gene_df,all_of( "KEGG_ko"), sep = ",", convert = TRUE)
  
  functions_name_corresp = read.csv("../ressources/KEGG_ko_final.csv", sep = ";")
  
  gene_df$KEGG_ko = functions_name_corresp$Definition_function[match(gene_df$KEGG_ko, functions_name_corresp$Code_function)]
  gene_df$KEGG_ko = as.factor(gene_df$KEGG_ko)

}

Reshaping the data frame by :

  • dropping rows with NA in the Prefered_name or the KEGG_Ko column

  • renaming piglets and the gene column

  • putting the gene column in the first column (instead of the last one).

gene_df = drop_na(gene_df)
print(paste0((dim(gene_df)[1]/dim_raw)*100, "% of the rows have been conserved (",dim(gene_df)[1],")"))
[1] "5.35% of the rows have been conserved (107)"
colnames(gene_df) = c(paste0("Piglet_", seq(34)), "Gene")
gene_df = gene_df[c(dim(gene_df)[2], 1:(dim(gene_df)[2])-1)] 

head(gene_df)

We then aggregate the duplicated genes by row.

gene_df = aggregate(gene_df[-1], by = list(gene_df$Gene), FUN = sum)
colnames(gene_df)[1] = "Gene"

gene_names = levels(gene_df$Gene) ## Saving the list of genes names for later
head(gene_df)

Finally, the data.frame is translated.

gene_df = as.data.frame(t(gene_df)) #translating df (i.e. indiv as rows and genes as columns)
colnames(gene_df) = gene_df[1,]
gene_df = gene_df[-1,]
gene_df$Piglet = rownames(gene_df)

head(gene_df)

Bacteria dataset

Importation of bacteria dataset

bacteria_df = read.csv(file="../refined_data/complete_taxonomy_X_sample.csv",
                    sep=";",
                    stringsAsFactors = TRUE,
                    na.strings = "NA",
                    check.names = F)

Manipulations on the bacteria dataset

We realize the same treatment as done on the gene dataset : dropping columns, aggregation of rows, renaming columns, translating data frame.

bacteria_df = droplevels.data.frame(subset(bacteria_df, kingdom == "Bacteria",
                                            select = -c(root, kingdom)) )
bacteria_df = aggregate(bacteria_df[,paste0("abond", seq(34))],
                         by = list(bacteria_df$genus),
                         FUN = sum)
colnames(bacteria_df) = c("bacteria", paste0("Piglet_", seq(34)))

bacteria_df = as.data.frame(t(bacteria_df))
colnames(bacteria_df) = bacteria_df["bacteria",]
bacteria_df = bacteria_df[-1,]
bacteria_df$Piglet = rownames(bacteria_df)
rownames(bacteria_df) = NULL

bacteria_names = colnames(bacteria_df[-1]) ## Saving the name of bacterias for later

head(bacteria_df)

Merging both data frames

We merge the dataframes by the Piglet column, shared by both.

data = merge(gene_df, bacteria_df, by = "Piglet", all = T) ## Merging dataframes by the name of the piglet.

data[,-1] = as.numeric(unlist(data[,-1])) ## Converting characters to numeric
data = Filter(function(x)!all(is.na(x)), data) ## Removing empty columns

rm(list=c("gene_df", "bacteria_df"))

head(data)

Correlating data data.frame

We calculate the correlations between genes and bacteria using a non-parametric method (Spearman).

cor_data = as.data.frame(cor(data[, -1], method = "spearman"))
Avis : l'écart type est nul
head(cor_data)

We put the row names as a variable called bacteria because the gene names and the bacteria names have been duplicated because of the correlation command.

cor_data$bacteria <- rownames(cor_data)
cor_data = cor_data[c(dim(cor_data)[2], 1:(dim(cor_data)[2])-1)]

head(cor_data)

We use the melt() function to verbose for each bacteria, all the gene and the associated correlation.

library(reshape2)

melted_data = melt(cor_data, id = "bacteria") ## Melting the data.frame

melted_data = drop_na(melted_data) ## Removing empty columns
melted_data$bacteria = as.factor(melted_data$bacteria) 
colnames(melted_data)[2] = "genes"

## Removing genes in bacteria column and reverse.
melted_data = subset(melted_data, bacteria %in% bacteria_names & genes %in% gene_names)
melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(melted_data)

rm(list=c("cor_data"))

head(melted_data)

We then export the current data frame.

write.table(melted_data, 
            file = "../refined_data/bacteria_X_gene_cor.tsv",
            col.names = TRUE,
            row.names = FALSE,
            sep="\t")

Filtering bacteria and genes

Filtering on correlation values

In order to do that, we filter the melted_data data frame to keep rows if the correlation value is more than the threshold or less than the negative threshold.

thres_keep = 0.6

filtered_melted_data = melted_data %>% subset(melted_data$value <= -thres_keep | melted_data$value >= thres_keep)

filtered_melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(filtered_melted_data)

rm(list=c("melted_data"))
head(filtered_melted_data)

We then subset melted_data using thresholds on both genes and bacteria. For that we will plot the distribution of correlation means.

library(ggplot2)

We plot the threshold on histograms to see where it lands

print(paste("Number of correlation with a value superior to the threshold (", thres_keep, ") : ", sum(filtered_melted_data$value >= thres_keep)))
[1] "Number of correlation with a value superior to the threshold ( 0.6 ) :  165"
print(paste("Number of correlation with a value inferior to the inversed threshold (", -thres_keep, ") : ", sum(filtered_melted_data$value <= -thres_keep)))
[1] "Number of correlation with a value inferior to the inversed threshold ( -0.6 ) :  8"

Filtering on correlation p-values

We create a data frame with the previous filtered rows.

selected_genes = levels(filtered_melted_data$genes)
selected_bacteria = levels(filtered_melted_data$bacteria)

tmp_data = data[,c(selected_genes, selected_bacteria)]

We calculate and then associate the p-value of the correlation to the correlation relation.

library("psych")

Avis : le package ‘psych’ a été compilé avec la version R 4.2.2
Attachement du package : ‘psych’

Les objets suivants sont masqués depuis ‘package:ggplot2’:

    %+%, alpha
## suppressWarnings is here to not show warnings about standard deviation being null (which slows down the function)
cor_res = suppressWarnings(corr.test(tmp_data[,-1], method = "spearman", ci = F))
cor_pval = as.data.frame( cor_res$p )
cor_pval$bacteria <- rownames(cor_pval)
cor_pval = cor_pval[c(dim(cor_pval)[2], 1:(dim(cor_pval)[2])-1)]

We keep correlation between genes and bacteria only if it is significant.

melted_pval = melt(cor_pval, id = "bacteria") ## Melting the data.frame

melted_pval = drop_na(melted_pval) ## Removing empty columns
melted_pval$bacteria = as.factor(melted_pval$bacteria) 
colnames(melted_pval)[2] = "genes"

melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, bacteria %in% bacteria_names & genes %in% gene_names)
colnames(melted_pval)[3] = "pvalue"
melted_pval = droplevels.data.frame(melted_pval)

filtered_melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, pvalue >= 0.05) # Keeping only significative results

rm(list=c("melted_pval", "tmp_data"))
Avis : object 'tmp_data' not found
head(filtered_melted_pval)

We merge the two data frames in order to get four columns : Bacteria, gene, value of the correlation and the p-value of the correlation

We will plot the distribution of correlation values.

hist(abs(filtered_melted_data$value), 
     breaks = 40)
Avis : no non-missing arguments to min; returning InfAvis : no non-missing arguments to max; returning -InfError in hist.default(abs(filtered_melted_data$value), breaks = 40) : 
  character(0)

We then export the filtered data.frame.

library(ggplot2)

filtered_melted_data_ordered = order(filtered_melted_data[,-c(1,2)], decreasing = TRUE)
filtered_melted_data = filtered_melted_data[filtered_melted_data_ordered[1:100],]

ggplot(filtered_melted_data, aes(genes, bacteria, fill= value)) +
  geom_tile(colour = "white", size = 0.5)+
  scale_fill_gradientn(name = "Correlation coefficient",# definition of the color gradient.
                       #trans = "log10", #chosing a logarythmic color scale
                       breaks = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1), 
                       labels = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1),
                       #na.value = "#43A3B9",# plotting the 0 in the lowest color of the gradient
                       colours = c("#43A3B9",  "#D0EC97", "#FFFFDF", "#FD945D", "#DC4E51", "#370303"),
  )+
  
  scale_x_discrete(expand=c(0, 0))+ # Removing blank space between data and X axis
  labs(fill="correlation coefficient", # Setting legend and title name
       title = "Correlation coefficients between genes and bacterias")+
  theme_grey(base_size=12)+ # Setting the base font size
  theme(line = element_blank(), # Removing the lines in between the boxes
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(), # Removing ticks on X axis
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, face="bold.italic", size = 30), # Removing X labels
